    body: 'Transformative purgation goes beyond ordinary ascetical effort to describe God\'s own purifying work within the soul. John of the Cross\'s passive nights of sense and spirit are the classic description: God acts like a fire that first causes pain as it encounters the soul\'s impurities but gradually transforms what it touches into itself. This purgation affects the deepest levels of the personality, including unconscious attachments, habitual patterns, and even the roots of the capital sins that surface during this painful process.',
